	Association of Infertility Prevalence by PID History
	In Table 2, infertility prevalence was defined as actively trying to conceive for ≥ 12 months without pregnancy. Overall, 5.35% (n=145) of women without history of PID were infertile, while 9.88% (n=33) of women with a PID history reported infertility. Unadjusted logistic regression indicated that women with a history of PID had twice the odds of infertility compared with women without PID (OR = 2.00; 95% CI: 1.34, 2.98). Adjustment for age yielded a very similar estimate (aOR = 1.94; 95% CI: 1.30, 2.89). In the fully adjusted model (including age, race/ethnicity, income-to-poverty ratio category, current health insurance status, and usual source of care), the association remained statistically significant (aOR = 1.90; 95% CI: 1.13, 3.18).
