Sensitivity Analysis 
To evaluate the robustness of the findings, the fully adjusted logistic regression model was re-fit using unweighted estimation and compared with the weighted survey model. Effect estimates from the unweighted model were similar in magnitude to those from the survey-weighted analysis (e.g., AOR 1.94 vs. 1.90), indicating that the association between PID and infertility was not sensitive to the application of NHANES sampling weights.
Discussion
This study aimed to examine the association between self-reported pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) and infertility among U.S. women aged 18–59 years using nationally representative NHANES data from 2017–2020 to determine if factors such as age, race, health insurance status, and socioeconomic status influence this relationship. We found that women with a history of PID had nearly twice the odds of reporting infertility compared to those without PID. Infertility prevalence was 9.88% among women with PID compared to 5.35% among women without PID. This pattern was consistent across unadjusted, age-adjusted, and fully adjusted survey-weighted logistic regression models. In the fully adjusted model, which accounted for age, race/ethnicity, income-to-poverty ratio, insurance status, and access to care, PID remained significantly associated with infertility (AOR = 1.90, 95% CI: 1.13–3.18). These findings support the study’s hypothesis that a history of PID is associated with increased odds of infertility.
Additionally, the results align with prior literature documenting the long-term reproductive consequences of PID. Previous studies have shown that untreated or recurrent PID can cause permanent tubal damage, which increases the risk of infertility through mechanisms such as scarring, inflammation, and adhesions 7. Research using laparoscopic examinations has demonstrated that even a single episode of PID can lead to tubal factor infertility years later, consistent with the elevated infertility prevalence observed in this study9. Additionally, epidemiologic studies have found that women with prior chlamydia or gonorrhea infections (two leading causes of PID) experience higher rates of tubal obstruction and subsequent infertility18. The present findings build on this evidence by offering updated, nationally representative estimates from recent NHANES cycles, including the years immediately preceding the COVID-19 pandemic. Findings from this study also compare closely with results from the NHANES 2013-2016 cross-sectional analysis measuring self-reported infertility and associated pelvic inflammatory disease in women of reproductive age3. Findings reported that both infertility and PID were positively associated in a nationally representative sample. In their study, approximately 13.8% of sexually experienced women reported infertility, a prevalence somewhat higher than the 6.33% observed in our sample, likely reflecting differences in age range and analytic definitions3. However, despite these differences in baseline prevalence, the strength of association between PID and infertility in their analysis was similar to our study, reinforcing the consistency of this relationship across multiple NHANES cycles. Our study builds on this foundation by incorporating more recent data and by examining whether socioeconomic and healthcare access factors modify this association. 
The results found that the strength of association was consistent even after adjusting for socioeconomic indicators and emphasizes the biological impact of PID. Although socioeconomic disadvantage is known to limit access to STI testing, delay care, and increase risk of untreated infections; PID continued to show an independent association with infertility even after these factors were accounted for and effect estimates were very similar before and after this adjustment11. This is consistent with literature documenting that once tubal damage has occurred, socioeconomic differences play less of a role in shaping infertility risk. However, it remains important to recognize that socioeconomic barriers, including limited insurance coverage, cost-related delays in seeking care, and reduced access to routine reproductive health services contribute to missed or delayed PID diagnosis. These structural inequities help explain why PID prevalence and its complications remain disproportionately higher in certain populations, underscoring the broader public health implications of the findings. Overall, the findings highlight the continued need for timely STI screening, appropriate PID management, and improved access to reproductive healthcare.
Limitations
Like most research studies, this analysis has limitations. First, the cross-sectional design prevents determination of temporal ordering; although it is biologically plausible that PID preceded infertility, the timing of each event cannot be confirmed. Second, both PID history and infertility were self-reported, which introduces potential recall bias and misclassification. Because PID is often asymptomatic, many infections may go undiagnosed, possibly underestimating the true effect. Third, NHANES does not distinguish infertility caused by tubal factor compared to infertility due to male partners or other medical conditions. As a result, some infertility cases may not be directly attributable to PID. 
Strengths
Despite these limitations, the study has several strengths. NHANES provides high-quality, nationally representative data, enhancing generalizability to U.S. women aged 18–59. The reproductive health questionnaire uses standardized measures of infertility, which improves consistency across participants. The analysis applied survey weights to ensure nationally representative population estimates and correct variance estimation. Additionally, multiple adjusted models were used to examine the robustness of associations, and unweighted models were run for sensitivity analyses, yielding consistent results. This strengthens confidence in the observed relationship. Importantly, this study contributes to contemporary evidence during a period in which PID surveillance data have been limited, particularly in the years surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic.
Conclusion
Overall, this study provides evidence that women with a history of PID have significantly greater odds of infertility compared to those without PID, even after adjusting for demographic, socioeconomic, and healthcare access factors. These findings reinforce the importance of early detection and treatment of sexually transmitted infections to prevent PID and its long-term reproductive consequences. Public health strategies that expand STI screening, improve partner treatment services, and reduce socioeconomic barriers to care may help prevent infertility stemming from untreated PID. Because contemporary U.S. population–level data linking PID and infertility remain limited, this study helps fill an important gap by providing updated, nationally representative estimates of this association15. Future research should include longitudinal studies with clinical confirmation of PID and detailed infertility etiologies to better understand causal pathways and develop targeted interventions. Clinical diagnosis of PID is still imprecise because there is no widely adopted, minimally invasive “gold standard” of detecting this disease besides laparoscopy15. This is inconvenient to many individuals seeking PID care due to the high cost because of anesthesia involvement and its invasiveness. Additionally, due to the lack of a solid diagnosis routine, the disease is frequently missed and causes women to live with the disease for many years, resulting in infertility15. Researchers and providers should focus on solidifying an affordable and early detecting diagnosis plan for women to avoid the increasing rates of PID associated with infertility. Additionally, research is needed to evaluate whether improved diagnostic tools, broader antimicrobial regimens, and more effective partner management strategies can reduce not only acute PID but also downstream infertility, particularly among women facing socioeconomic barriers to timely care15. Strengthening reproductive healthcare access and prioritizing prevention efforts may ultimately help reduce the burden of preventable infertility among U.S. women.
Lay Summary
Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is an infection of the female reproductive organs that can cause long-term health problems, including infertility. This project used national survey data from U.S. women ages 18–59 to examine whether women who had ever been diagnosed with PID were more likely to experience infertility. Infertility was defined as trying to become pregnant for at least one year without success. The study included more than 2,800 women and compared infertility rates between those with and without a history of PID. Women who had previously been told they had PID were almost twice as likely to report infertility compared to women without PID. This pattern remained even after accounting for age, race/ethnicity, income level, health insurance, and access to regular medical care. These findings highlight the importance of early testing and treatment for sexually transmitted infections, which can prevent PID and reduce the risk of infertility later in life.





















